Beyond Blob Storage, Azure provides several other storage services inside a Storage Account, each designed for a specific workload. Azure Files is a fully managed file share service accessible over S-M-B or N-F-S. Azure Managed Disks are block storage volumes attached to virtual machines. Azure Queue Storage is a simple durable message queue. And Azure Table Storage is a serverless NoSQL key-value store. All of these live inside a Storage Account and share the same redundancy, encryption, and network security model as Blob Storage.

Let us start with Azure Files.

Azure Files is a fully managed file share service accessible over S-M-B version 3 on Windows, Linux, and macOS, and over N-F-S version 4.1 on Linux and macOS. It is designed to replace on-premises file servers — you can lift and shift legacy applications that depend on a file share, provide shared configuration files or home directories, or use it as a persistent volume in Azure Kubernetes Service.

Azure Files comes in four tiers. Transaction Optimised and Hot and Cool are all H-D-D-backed and suitable for general-purpose workloads, collaboration, and online archival respectively. The Premium tier is S-S-D-backed with sub-millisecond latency and up to 100,000 I-O-P-S, making it suitable for latency-sensitive workloads such as databases and development tools. Premium file shares require a separate Premium File Shares storage account — they cannot be created in a Standard G-P-v2 account.

One important network consideration for S-M-B is port 445. S-M-B requires outbound port 445 to be open, but many I-S-P-s and corporate firewalls block this port. For on-premises access when port 445 is blocked, there are two solutions: use a V-P-N or ExpressRoute connection so traffic flows over a private network, or use Azure File Sync.

Azure File Sync extends Azure Files into a distributed, cached file system. You install the File Sync agent on one or more Windows Server machines. Files are cached locally on each server so access is fast even over a wide-area network. Cloud tiering is a key feature — it replaces infrequently accessed files on the local server with a lightweight pointer and downloads them from Azure on demand when accessed, freeing local disk space. Multiple servers in different offices can sync the same Azure file share, replacing a traditional Distributed File System setup.

For authentication, the recommended approach for domain-joined virtual machines is Entra I-D Kerberos authentication — users sign in with their Entra I-D credentials and Azure issues Kerberos tickets. Hybrid environments can use on-premises Active Directory Domain Services Kerberos so existing domain-joined machines access Azure Files with their existing A-D accounts. For non-domain-joined systems and scripted mounts, the storage account key is used.

Now let us look at Azure Managed Disks.

Managed Disks are block storage volumes for Azure virtual machines — the Azure equivalent of A-W-S E-B-S. The word "managed" means Azure handles storage account placement, redundancy, and capacity behind the scenes. You create a disk, specify the size and type, and attach it to a V-M.

There are five disk types. Ultra Disk is the highest performance tier with up to 400,000 I-O-P-S and 10,000 megabytes per second throughput — used for S-A-P H-A-N-A, top-tier database engines, and real-time analytics. Premium S-S-D v2 offers up to 80,000 I-O-P-S with configurable I-O-P-S and throughput, making it flexible for most production databases. Premium S-S-D is the traditional S-S-D option with up to 20,000 I-O-P-S, suitable for production databases and enterprise applications. Standard S-S-D goes up to 6,000 I-O-P-S and is appropriate for web servers, lightly loaded apps, and dev and test. Standard H-D-D tops out at 500 I-O-P-S and is used for backups, infrequent access, and cold storage.

Every virtual machine has three disk roles. The O-S disk contains the operating system and is persistently attached to the V-M. The temporary disk is a local S-S-D on the physical host — it is not managed storage, not replicated, and its contents are wiped whenever the V-M is stopped or redeployed. Never store data that must survive a V-M restart on the temporary disk. Data disks are additional managed volumes you attach to the V-M and they persist independently.

For redundancy, Managed Disks support L-R-S by default — three copies in one data centre. Zone Redundant Storage for disks is available for Premium S-S-D and Standard S-S-D, distributing copies across three availability zones. Ultra Disk and Premium S-S-D v2 support zone pinning, where the disk is placed in a specific availability zone alongside the V-M.

Snapshots are point-in-time copies of a managed disk used for backup or creating new disks. Incremental snapshots only capture the changed pages since the last snapshot, making them significantly cheaper and faster for large disks. Images capture a fully generalised V-M — one that has been sysprepped or depersonalised — into a reusable template stored in Azure Compute Gallery for deploying multiple identical V-Ms.

Disks support multiple encryption layers. Azure Storage encryption is on by default — 256-bit A-E-S at rest with either Microsoft-managed or customer-managed keys via Key Vault. Azure Disk Encryption adds an O-S-level layer using BitLocker on Windows and dm-crypt on Linux, with keys stored in Key Vault. Encryption at host encrypts the temporary disk and disk caches at the physical host level before the data reaches the Azure Storage network.

Now let us look at Azure Queue Storage.

Azure Queue Storage is a simple, durable message queue for decoupling application components. It is the lightweight alternative to Azure Service Bus. Each message can be up to 64 kilobytes, and a queue can hold up to 500 terabytes of data. By default messages expire after 7 days. When a consumer retrieves a message it becomes invisible to other consumers for a configurable visibility timeout period, giving the consumer time to process and delete it. If the consumer does not delete it within that window, the message becomes visible again and can be reprocessed. This gives Queue Storage at-least-once delivery semantics — messages may be delivered more than once.

The key difference between Queue Storage and Service Bus is that Queue Storage is a simple first-in-first-out queue with no guaranteed ordering, no dead-letter queue, and no topics. Service Bus adds guaranteed message ordering using sessions, a dead-letter queue for messages that fail processing, publish-subscribe with topics and subscriptions, and transactional support. Use Queue Storage for simple high-volume decoupling where occasional duplicate delivery is acceptable and price matters. Use Service Bus for enterprise messaging scenarios that need ordering, dead-lettering, or topics.

Finally, let us look at Azure Table Storage.

Azure Table Storage is a serverless NoSQL key-value store for structured non-relational data. It is the predecessor to Azure Cosmos D-B Table A-P-I. The data model has Tables containing Entities — each entity has a Partition Key, a Row Key, an auto-maintained Timestamp, and up to 252 custom properties.

The Partition Key determines how data is physically stored and is the primary mechanism for query performance. Queries that filter on Partition Key plus Row Key — called point queries — are the fastest. Queries on Partition Key plus a Row Key range are also efficient. Full table scans that do not specify a Partition Key are slow and expensive, so partition key design is critical.

Table Storage is very low cost with no secondary indexes and a 99.9% S-L-A. Cosmos D-B Table A-P-I is the upgraded version with single-digit millisecond latency, global distribution, a 99.999% S-L-A, secondary indexes, and configurable throughput. For new workloads that need global distribution or stronger guarantees, use Cosmos D-B Table A-P-I. Use Table Storage for simple cost-sensitive scenarios where its limitations are acceptable.

All Azure Storage services — Blob, Files, Queues, Tables — share the same network security model. By default storage accounts accept traffic from all networks. You can restrict this by setting the default action to Deny and then adding explicit allow rules for specific I-P ranges, V-Net subnets via service endpoints, or trusted Azure services. Private endpoints assign the storage account a private I-P within your V-Net — each storage service gets its own private endpoint sub-resource. Certain Azure services like Azure Backup, Monitor, and Event Grid can be allowed through the trusted services bypass without opening the firewall broadly.

To summarise. Use Azure Files for shared S-M-B or N-F-S file systems. Use Azure File Sync to extend Azure Files to on-premises Windows Servers with cloud tiering. Use Managed Disks for V-M storage — never use the temporary disk for persistent data. Choose the disk type based on I-O-P-S requirements: Ultra Disk and Premium S-S-D v2 for high-performance databases, Premium S-S-D for general production, Standard S-S-D for web workloads, Standard H-D-D for backups. Use incremental snapshots to back up large disks cost-effectively. Use Queue Storage for simple decoupling and Service Bus when you need ordering, dead-lettering, or topics. And use Table Storage for simple key-value workloads, or Cosmos D-B Table A-P-I when you need global distribution.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure Virtual Networks and Subnets — the networking foundation of every Azure deployment.
